Self-Driving Car Engineer Nanodegree¶

Project: Finding Lane Lines on the Road¶

In the project below, I built a Python pipeline to identify lane lines in video streams. The end goal is to be able to extract and draw the line equations which describe the left and right lane lines. With these equations, a self-driving car would subsequently be able to determine if the vehicle is within or outside of its lane lines.

First we learn to detect and average lane lines through images, then we run our pipeline through a video stream.

  • Analyze Images

    • Convert to Grayscale
    • Gaussian smoothing
    • Canny Edge Detection
    • Select Relevant Regions
    • Hough Transform line detection

  • Analyze Videos

Helper Functions¶

Below are some helper functions used in my pipeline. I will go over them in more detail while processing a single image.

In [3]:
def grayscale(img):
    """Applies the Grayscale transform
    This will return an image with only one color channel
    but NOTE: to see the returned image as grayscale
    (assuming your grayscaled image is called 'gray')
    you should call plt.imshow(gray, cmap='gray')"""
    return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)
    # Or use BGR2GRAY if you read an image with cv2.imread()
    # return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    
def canny(img, low_threshold, high_threshold):
    """Applies the Canny transform"""
    return cv2.Canny(img, low_threshold, high_threshold)

def gaussian_blur(img, kernel_size):
    """Applies a Gaussian Noise kernel"""
    return cv2.GaussianBlur(img, (kernel_size, kernel_size), 0)

def region_of_interest(img, vertices):
    """
    Applies an image mask.
    
    Only keeps the region of the image defined by the polygon
    formed from `vertices`. The rest of the image is set to black.
    """
    #defining a blank mask to start with
    mask = np.zeros_like(img)   
    
    #defining a 3 channel or 1 channel color to fill the mask with depending on the input image
    if len(img.shape) > 2:
        channel_count = img.shape[2]  # i.e. 3 or 4 depending on your image
        ignore_mask_color = (255,) * channel_count
    else:
        ignore_mask_color = 255
        
    #filling pixels inside the polygon defined by "vertices" with the fill color    
    cv2.fillPoly(mask, vertices, ignore_mask_color)
    
    #returning the image only where mask pixels are nonzero
    masked_image = cv2.bitwise_and(img, mask)
    return masked_image


def draw_lines(img, lines, color=[255, 0, 0], thickness=2):
    """
    Given the hough transformation array of line coordinates, 
    identifies what the left and right lane equations are and draws them out.
    """
    # Initialize empty lists
    left_slope_list = []
    right_slope_list = []
    left_b_list = []
    right_b_list = []
    
    # Calculate slopes and categorize as left or right if != 0 
    for index, line in enumerate(lines):
        for x1,y1,x2,y2 in line:
            # If x1=x2, then slope will be infinity--> Won't consider perfectly vertical lines in this project
            if (x1!=x2):
                temp_slope = (y1-y2)/(x1-x2)
                # Decreasing slope = most likely left lane
                if (temp_slope < 0 ):
                    left_slope_list.append(temp_slope)
                    left_b_list.append(y1-temp_slope*x1)
                # Append to right side
                elif (temp_slope>0): 
                    right_slope_list.append(temp_slope)
                    right_b_list.append(y1-temp_slope*x1)
       
    ## Intercept Groupings Check ##
    # Part 1: ID Valid intercept Grouping #
    # Intuition: 
    # If there are parallel left lane lines (consider a lane line, alongside a highway barrier shadow),
    # there should be noticable groupings in the intercept value.
    # The inner lane could be ID'd by a larger intercept, since it crosses x=0 at a larger y.
    # Otherwise, the function would take the average of the intercepts and slopes which could dramatically 
    # skew the identified left lane line. 
    temp_sorted_left_b = np.sort(left_b_list)
    
    # After sorting all intercepts, find the consecutive differences between each element
    # Intuition: 
    # If the parallel lines are spaced apart, then if we take the average of them, we will result in a skewed lane line.
    # 100 is an aribrary value that currently suffices to ID parallel lines that are spaced apart
    # It would be good downstream to experiment with this value and tune it further based on more training sets.
    temp_sorted_left_b = np.split(temp_sorted_left_b, np.where(np.diff(temp_sorted_left_b) > 100)[0]+1)
    
    # Previous hough lane and canny parameters should have removed most outliers. This function assumes
    # that the groupings collected at this point represent actual lines that should be considered. 
    # Since we want the larger lane lines, extract them here.
    if( len(temp_sorted_left_b)>1):
  
        # Part 2: Given ID'd intercept grouping, collect associated slope #
        # Find original indices for intercept elements so we can retrieve related slope 
        indices = [i for i, j in enumerate(left_b_list) if j in temp_sorted_left_b[len(temp_sorted_left_b)-1]]
        left_slope_array = np.asarray(left_slope_list)[indices]
        left_b_array = np.asarray(left_b_list)[indices]
    else:
        # No groupings ID'd, take the original lists
        left_b_array = np.asarray(left_b_list)
        left_slope_array = np.asarray(left_slope_list)
    
    # Calculate median slope
    left_slope = np.median(left_slope_array)
    
    # Remove outliers
    i = 0
    while(i<len(left_slope_array)):
               
        # If slope is within +/- 20% of the median, should be ok
        # Might be better to tune this value to some constant rather than a relative value.
        # Since slopes can range from something like -0.3 (left lane) to 400 (right lane),
        # 20% is pretty arbitrary and inconsistent. 
        # Nevertheless, I kept it here because it worked fairly well on the test videos
        if abs(abs(left_slope_array[i])-abs(left_slope)) > abs(left_slope)*.2:

            # Set slope to 0, will be discarded later
            left_slope_array = np.delete(left_slope_array, i)
            left_b_array = np.delete(left_b_array, i)
        else:
            #nothing deleted, increase increment
            i += 1
                    
    # Calculate median intercept
    left_b = np.median(left_b_array)
    i = 0

    while(i < len(left_b_array)):
        # If intercept is within +/- 15 pixels of the median, should be ok
        # Using 15 px rather than a percentage of the original intercept to make the algorithm behave similarly
        # for large and small intercepts. This constant can be further tuned with additional training data.
        if abs(abs(left_b_array[i])-abs(left_b)) > 15:
            left_slope_array = np.delete(left_slope_array, i)
            left_b_array = np.delete(left_b_array, i)
        else: 
            #nothing deleted, increase increment
            i +=1
    
    # recalculate average
    left_slope = np.mean(left_slope_array)
    left_b = np.mean(left_b_array)
    
    ### --------------------------------------------------------------------------------- ###
    ### Repeat above for the right side ###
    temp_sorted_right_b = np.sort(right_b_list)

    # Get groupings
    temp_sorted_right_b = np.split(temp_sorted_right_b, np.where(np.diff(temp_sorted_right_b) > 100)[0]+1)
    
    # Get the smaller groupings to find the right lane
    if( len(temp_sorted_right_b)>1):
 
        # Find original indices for intercept elements so we can retrieve related slope 
        indices = [i for i, j in enumerate(right_b_list) if j in temp_sorted_right_b[0]]
        right_slope_array = np.asarray(right_slope_list)[indices]
        right_b_array = np.asarray(right_b_list)[indices]
        
    else:
        right_b_array = np.asarray(right_b_list)
        right_slope_array = np.asarray(right_slope_list)
    
    # Calculate median slope
    right_slope = np.median(right_slope_array)
    
    # Remove outliers
    i = 0
    while(i<len(right_slope_array)):
        
        if abs(abs(right_slope_array[i])-abs(right_slope)) > abs(right_slope)*.2:

            # Set slope to 0, will be discarded later
            right_slope_array = np.delete(right_slope_array, i)
            right_b_array = np.delete(right_b_array, i)

        else:
            #nothing deleted, increase increment
            i += 1
         

    # Calculate median intercept
    right_b = np.median(right_b_array)

    i = 0
    while(i < len(right_b_array)):
        if abs(abs(right_b_array[i])-abs(right_b)) > 15:

            right_slope_array = np.delete(right_slope_array, i)
            right_b_array = np.delete(right_b_array, i)
        else: 
            #nothing deleted, increase increment
            i +=1
    
    # Get final average right slope/intercept
    right_slope = np.mean(right_slope_array)
    right_b = np.mean(right_b_array)

    # draw lines --> Extrapolates lane range within the masked region
    ysize = img.shape[1]  
    lines_img = np.copy(img)*0

    if( not(math.isnan(left_b) or math.isnan(left_slope)) ):
        lines_img = cv2.line(lines_img, (int((ysize-left_b)/left_slope), ysize), (int(-left_b/left_slope),0), color=(255,0,0), thickness=5)
    if( not(math.isnan(right_b) or math.isnan(right_slope)) ):
        lines_img = cv2.line(lines_img, (int((ysize-right_b)/right_slope), ysize), (int(-right_b/right_slope),0), color=(255,0,0), thickness=5)

    return lines_img
def hough_lines(img, rho, theta, threshold, min_line_len, max_line_gap):
    """
    `img` should be the output of a Canny transform.
        
    Returns an image with hough lines drawn.
    """
    lines = cv2.HoughLinesP(img, rho, theta, threshold, np.array([]), min_line_len, max_line_gap)
    line_img = np.zeros((img.shape[0], img.shape[1], 3), dtype=np.uint8)
    line_img = draw_lines(line_img, lines)
    return line_img

# Python 3 has support for cool math symbols.

def weighted_img(img, initial_img, =0.8, =1., =0.):
    """
    `img` is the output of the hough_lines(), An image with lines drawn on it.
    Should be a blank image (all black) with lines drawn on it.
    
    `initial_img` should be the image before any processing.
    
    The result image is computed as follows:
    
    initial_img *  + img *  + 
    NOTE: initial_img and img must be the same shape!
    """
    return cv2.addWeighted(initial_img, , img, , )

Step 1: Convert to grayscale¶

Since lane lines can appear in many colors and shades, we convert our image from an RGB image to a grayscale image. This simplifies the image so that we could more easily detect edges in the image which could be lane lines.

Further down, I noticed that converting the leftYellowSolid.mp4 video from its original color frame to grayscale was not sufficient to bring out the yellow edges. Consequently, I ended up splitting the RGB channels and only used the red and green values as input to the grayscale function. This seemed to make it easier for the pipeline to detect both yellow and white lane lines.

Step 2: Apply Gaussian Filter¶

I used a larger kernel size (15) here to exagerate the effects of applying a Gaussian Filter. In the actual pipeline below, we use a kernel with size 7.

The Gaussian Filter kernel is a matrix which represents the Gaussian curve that is convoluted over the image to remove noise. A larger kernel will smooth the image more, but also renders the image more fuzzy, and therefore the edges harder to detect-- and if detected, less accurate. Once this mask is applied, pixels in the image are blurred, such that small variances between pixels are muted, and larger differences are easier to capture.

Step 3: Detect Edges using Canny Edge Detection Algorithm¶

The canny edge detection algorithm first calculates the gradients, or changes in intensity between pixels. From these gradients, it takes two threshold t1 & t2, where t1>t2. All pixels with gradients below t2 are blacked out. Pixels between t1 and t2 are set to 255 (white) if they are adjacent to a pixel that has a gradient larger than t2. Read the opencv documentation for more information.

In [7]:

high_threshold=140

Step 3: Extract Region of Interest¶

For this project, we are interested in the quadrilateral region in front of the car where a typical lane line will appear. We now black out all pixels outside the region directly in front the car camera, (which we assume is mounted at the center front of the car). This will help minimize other lines which may confuse our draw_lines function downstream and skew the detected lane lines.

*In the challenge video, we had to redefine the region to ignore the bottom 100 pixels of the image since the hood of the car was visible in the video. If we did not do this, the edges of the hood would have skewed our detected lane lines.

def process_image(image):
    # NOTE: The output you return should be a color image (3 channel) for processing video below

    # Define a kernel size for Gaussian smoothing / blurring
    kernel_size =7# Must be an odd number (3, 5, 7...)

    low_threshold=100
    high_threshold=140

    ysize = image.shape[0]
    xsize = image.shape[1]
    # Explicitly set array datatypes to int 32, otherwise will default casut to 64 bit.
    # Use this vertices definition if running the challenge video. We modified it here since the camera was mounted 
    # differently, resulting in the edges of the hood to be detectable. 
    # By using the vertices definition below, we ignore the edges of the hood.
    # vertices = np.array([[[0,650],[xsize*2/5,ysize*3/5],[xsize*3/5,ysize*3/5],[xsize, 650]]],dtype=np.int32) 
    # Normal: Use this definition for the solidYellowLeft and SolidWhiteRight videos, since the hood is not visible
    vertices = np.array([[[0,ysize],[xsize*2/5,ysize*3/5],[xsize*3/5,ysize*3/5],[xsize, ysize]]],dtype=np.int32)

    # Hough Parameters
    rho=1 # Distance resolution of Hough space grid-- keeping 1 as base unit
    theta=np.pi/180 # Angular resolution of Hough space grid-- keeping as 1 deg base unit
    # Chose 35 because it seems to catch longer lines and not little dashes which might through off the slope estimate
    threshold = 35 # Minimum number of intersections needed for a candidate line
    min_line_len = 30
    max_line_gap = 25
    
    # Get Color Channels
    r,g,b= cv2.split(image)

    # Convert the current image to grayscale
    # This combination of RGB values brought out the yellow and white lines simulatesouly the best given my informal trials
    gray = grayscale(np.dstack([g,r,r]))
    # gray = grayscale(image)
    # print('Grayscale', type(image), 'with dimensions:', gray.shape)
    
    blur_gray = gaussian_blur(gray, kernel_size)
    # print('Gaussian_blr', type(image), 'with dimensions:', blur_gray.shape)

    edges = canny(blur_gray, low_threshold, high_threshold)
    # print('Canny', type(image), 'with dimensions:', edges.shape)

    region_select = region_of_interest(edges, vertices)
    # print('Region Of INterest', type(image), 'with dimensions:', region_select.shape)

    lines = hough_lines(region_select, rho, theta, threshold, min_line_len, max_line_gap)
    # print('Hough', type(image), 'with dimensions:', lines.shape)

    
    lines = region_of_interest(lines,vertices)

    result = weighted_img(image, lines)
    # print('Weighted', type(image), 'with dimensions:', result.shape)

    return result
